With dot notation, it's better if the assumption which is used for dot notation comes first, as otherwise this leads to cryptic error messages in some situtations.
ditto


```suggestion
/-- A family `ð“• : Î¹ â†’ Î² â†’ Î±` is uniformly equicontinuous on `S` iff the function `swap ð“• : Î² â†’ Î¹ â†’ Î±`
```
What about moving `Î±'`, `X'` and `Î²'` declaration to the `variable` line?

```suggestion
family `ð“•'`, obtained by composing each function of `ð“•` by `u`, is equicontinuous. -/
```
Looks to me that precomposing is on the wrong side. Same thing below.

Shouldn't this one be in the `Set.EquicontinuousWithinAt` namespace, since you're applying it to sets of functions? If you agree, this means you don't need to put on the prime on the other version in the `EquicontinuousWithinAt` namespace.
Same thing below for all the other variations.

I'm not a big fan of this, because then `EquicontinuousWithinAt.closure` changes meaning if you're in namespace `Set` (opening `Set` is okay though), and the difference between the two is hard to tell when used with dot notation. Also, the current spelling does work fine with dot notation because `Set.EquicontinuousWithinAt` is an `abbrev`.

My problem is more in the other direction: if you have an assumption `H` that something (which is not a set of functions, but rather a family of functions) is equicontinuous and you try `H.closure`, then this will fails with a weird error message. With my proposition, `H.closure` should do the right thing in any case.

Anyway, I will follow whatever you think is best.
(I think `protected` would protect us against your fear that the meaning would depend on whether you are in a namespace or not).

Ah yes, this is a good point. Do you think I should swap the `closure` and `closure'`, the idea being that, even if it's not always the easier to use, the current `closure'` covers strictly more cases?

The problem with `protected` is that I don't think it applies once you do `namespace Set`.
For example:
```lean
protected def B.foo : Nat := 1
protected def A.B.foo : Nat := 2

#eval B.foo -- 1

open A
#eval B.foo -- 1

namespace A
#eval B.foo -- 2
end A
```
This is especially concerning because working in any theorem named `Set.bla` puts you in namespace `Set` for the duration of the proof...

I think I would keep the current meaning of `closure'` and `closure` (because `closure` is more common and easier to use), but I would replace `EquicontinuousWithinAt.closure` with `Set.EquicontinuousWithinAt.closure` to minimize the risk that someones calls `H.closure` when `H` is about a family of functions instead of a set of functions. Of course, it's not perfect (as you say, in the namespace `Set`, it doesn't protect you against the mistake), but it would still be an improvement over the current situation. You have convinced me that having both named `closure` but separated only by the namespace would be too prone to confusion.
Sounds good to me, I'll do that.
